        "text": "Best I can tell, yes, this should improve the situation. The source references should be fine (taken from the Subversion side of the merge). A full rebase gave me some conflict markers (`#-#-#-#-#`) in a few stale translations for removed strings; `msguniq --use-first` would avoid this (except for the markers in `*lt.po`, which come from the Subversion repo). There were complaints from `msguniq` about syntax errors due to Git merge conflict markers in the middle of `*.po` files; these may cause a phantom change in translation history, but as long as there is a later valid version of the file, the rest of the translation will be fine. There also are a number of <https:\/\/savannah.gnu.org\/bugs\/index.php?printer=1&amp;func=detailitem&amp;item_id=57990|warnings about \"invalid multibyte sequence\"> when the base (Subversion side) `*.po` file is missing the header entry specifying the encoding _and_ the merged-in (Weblate side) file is invalid due to a syntax error; they don't cause any additional changes to the translations.",
